            {
              "id": "IdenticalConditionalBranches",
              "shortDescription": {
                "text": "Conditional statement ignores the condition"
              },
              "fullDescription": {
                "text": "\n            Conditional statement that does the same thing when the condition is true and false\n            is either incorrect (one of the branches should be changed) or redundant\n            (can be replaced by one of its branches).\n        "
              },
              "helpUri": "https://docs.pmd-code.org/snapshot/pmd_rules_java_errorprone.html#identicalconditionalbranches",
              "help": {
                "text": "\n            Conditional statement that does the same thing when the condition is true and false\n            is either incorrect (one of the branches should be changed) or redundant\n            (can be replaced by one of its branches).\n        "
              },
              "properties": {
                "ruleset": "Error Prone",
                "priority": 3,
                "tags": [
                  "Error Prone"
                ]
              },
              "defaultConfiguration": {
                "level": "warning"
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "GodClass",
              "shortDescription": {
                "text": "Possible God Class (WMC=57, ATFD=27, TCC=28.571%)"
              },
              "fullDescription": {
                "text": "\nThe God Class rule detects the God Class design flaw using metrics. God classes do too many things,\nare very big and overly complex. They should be split apart to be more object-oriented.\nThe rule uses the detection strategy described in \"Object-Oriented Metrics in Practice\".\nThe violations are reported against the entire class.\n\nThe rule uses metrics to implement its detection strategy. The violation message\ngives information about the values of these metrics:\n* WMC: a class complexity measure, see {% jdoc java::lang.java.metrics.JavaMetrics#WEIGHED_METHOD_COUNT %}\n* ATFD: a measure of how much data external data the class uses, see {% jdoc java::lang.java.metrics.JavaMetrics#ACCESS_TO_FOREIGN_DATA %}\n* TCC: a measure of how tightly related the methods are, see {% jdoc java::lang.java.metrics.JavaMetrics#TIGHT_CLASS_COHESION %}\n\nThe rule identifies a god class by looking for classes which have all of the following properties:\n* High WMC\n* High ATFD\n* Low TCC\n\nSee also the reference:\n\nMichele Lanza and Radu Marinescu. *Object-Oriented Metrics in Practice:\nUsing Software Metrics to Characterize, Evaluate, and Improve the Design\nof Object-Oriented Systems.* Springer, Berlin, 1 edition, October 2006. Page 80.\n        "
              },
              "helpUri": "https://docs.pmd-code.org/snapshot/pmd_rules_java_design.html#godclass",
              "help": {
                "text": "\nThe God Class rule detects the God Class design flaw using metrics. God classes do too many things,\nare very big and overly complex. They should be split apart to be more object-oriented.\nThe rule uses the detection strategy described in \"Object-Oriented Metrics in Practice\".\nThe violations are reported against the entire class.\n\nThe rule uses metrics to implement its detection strategy. The violation message\ngives information about the values of these metrics:\n* WMC: a class complexity measure, see {% jdoc java::lang.java.metrics.JavaMetrics#WEIGHED_METHOD_COUNT %}\n* ATFD: a measure of how much data external data the class uses, see {% jdoc java::lang.java.metrics.JavaMetrics#ACCESS_TO_FOREIGN_DATA %}\n* TCC: a measure of how tightly related the methods are, see {% jdoc java::lang.java.metrics.JavaMetrics#TIGHT_CLASS_COHESION %}\n\nThe rule identifies a god class by looking for classes which have all of the following properties:\n* High WMC\n* High ATFD\n* Low TCC\n\nSee also the reference:\n\nMichele Lanza and Radu Marinescu. *Object-Oriented Metrics in Practice:\nUsing Software Metrics to Characterize, Evaluate, and Improve the Design\nof Object-Oriented Systems.* Springer, Berlin, 1 edition, October 2006. Page 80.\n        "
              },
              "properties": {
                "ruleset": "Design",
                "priority": 3,
                "tags": [
                  "Design"
                ]
              },
              "defaultConfiguration": {
                "level": "warning"
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "TooManyMethods",
              "shortDescription": {
                "text": "This class has too many methods, consider refactoring it."
              },
              "fullDescription": {
                "text": "\nA class with too many methods is probably a good suspect for refactoring, in order to reduce its\ncomplexity and find a way to have more fine grained objects.\n        "
              },
              "helpUri": "https://docs.pmd-code.org/snapshot/pmd_rules_java_design.html#toomanymethods",
              "help": {
                "text": "\nA class with too many methods is probably a good suspect for refactoring, in order to reduce its\ncomplexity and find a way to have more fine grained objects.\n        "
              },
              "properties": {
                "ruleset": "Design",
                "priority": 3,
                "tags": [
                  "Design"
                ]
              },
              "defaultConfiguration": {
                "level": "warning"
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "LongVariable",
              "shortDescription": {
                "text": "Avoid excessively long variable names like orderedListCounters"
              },
              "fullDescription": {
                "text": "\nFields, formal arguments, or local variable names that are too long can make the code difficult to follow.\n        "
              },
              "helpUri": "https://docs.pmd-code.org/snapshot/pmd_rules_java_codestyle.html#longvariable",
              "help": {
                "text": "\nFields, formal arguments, or local variable names that are too long can make the code difficult to follow.\n        "
              },
              "properties": {
                "ruleset": "Code Style",
                "priority": 3,
                "tags": [
                  "Code Style"
                ]
              },
              "defaultConfiguration": {
                "level": "warning"
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "LongVariable",
              "shortDescription": {
                "text": "Avoid excessively long variable names like listIndentationLevel"
              },
              "fullDescription": {
                "text": "\nFields, formal arguments, or local variable names that are too long can make the code difficult to follow.\n        "
              },
              "helpUri": "https://docs.pmd-code.org/snapshot/pmd_rules_java_codestyle.html#longvariable",
              "help": {
                "text": "\nFields, formal arguments, or local variable names that are too long can make the code difficult to follow.\n        "
              },
              "properties": {
                "ruleset": "Code Style",
                "priority": 3,
                "tags": [
                  "Code Style"
                ]
              },
              "defaultConfiguration": {
                "level": "warning"
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "RedundantFieldInitializer",
              "shortDescription": {
                "text": "Avoid using redundant field initializer for 'listIndentationLevel'"
              },
              "fullDescription": {
                "text": "\nJava will initialize fields with known default values so any explicit initialization of those same defaults\nis redundant and results in a larger class file (approximately three additional bytecode instructions per field).\n        "
              },
              "helpUri": "https://docs.pmd-code.org/snapshot/pmd_rules_java_performance.html#redundantfieldinitializer",
              "help": {
                "text": "\nJava will initialize fields with known default values so any explicit initialization of those same defaults\nis redundant and results in a larger class file (approximately three additional bytecode instructions per field).\n        "
              },
              "properties": {
                "ruleset": "Performance",
                "priority": 3,
                "tags": [
                  "Performance"
                ]
              },
              "defaultConfiguration": {
                "level": "warning"
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "LongVariable",
              "shortDescription": {
                "text": "Avoid excessively long variable names like isFirstBlockElement"
              },
              "fullDescription": {
                "text": "\nFields, formal arguments, or local variable names that are too long can make the code difficult to follow.\n        "
              },
              "helpUri": "https://docs.pmd-code.org/snapshot/pmd_rules_java_codestyle.html#longvariable",
              "help": {
                "text": "\nFields, formal arguments, or local variable names that are too long can make the code difficult to follow.\n        "
              },
              "properties": {
